LAGOS – There was uproar on Wednesday in Sapele, Delta State,, as protesting guards of Seplat Energy stormed the offices of the oil company to demand payment for providing surveillance for Seplat pipelines and oil impacted communities. The protesting workers were seen displaying placards and banners with different inscriptions such as “Seplat pay our increased salary and arrears,” and We are due for PPEs every six months”, “GMOU with pipeline communities must be actualized”, among others. Addressing the protesters, Mr. Yahaya Ismail, the Production Operation Manager of Seplat Energy, appealed for calm, adding that their demands were already been looked into. Seplat Considering Purchase Of ExxonMobil’s Nigerian Shallow… Seplat Confirms Ongoing Talks To Acquire ExxonMobil’s Nigerian… Ismail urged to the workers to remain calm, saying that the various issues raised will be addressed at a meeting with the management of the oil company, leaders, chairmen and stakeholders of the pipeline and impacted communities on Friday in Sapele. He disclosed that invitation letters had already been circulated. However, Mr. Alex Igbaran, chairman of Jakpa-Mereji Pipeline and Impacted Communities, while speaking with journalists, said that the protesting workers were demanding their rights, maintaining that, Seplat has failed to keep its promises over the years. Igbaran listed the reasons the workers were protesting to include failure by the oil company to increase the surveillance guards’ salaries and others.